  "market_context": "During London session, EURUSD swept buy-side liquidity above prior highs, then reversed lower, forming a bullish FVG that was later disrespected (closed below), creating an inversion. Price retested the consequent encroachment (0.5 level) of the inverted FVG before targeting sell-side liquidity.",
  "key_observation": "Price closed below a bullish fair value gap (BISI), inverting it into resistance; the 50% consequent encroachment of that inverted gap acted as a high-probability entry zone for a short trade.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identified a bullish fair value gap (BISI) on the 5-minute EURUSD chart between approximately 1.08662–1.08800, formed after a sweep of buy-side liquidity near 1.08921.",
    "Step 2: Observed price closing below the bullish FVG (at ~1.08662), thereby inverting it and converting it into a resistance zone.",
    "Step 3: Marked the consequent encroachment (0.5 level) of the inverted FVG—approximately 1.08700–1.08795—as the optimal trade entry zone.",
    "Step 4: Entered a short trade at the consequent encroachment level with stop above the recent swing low (1.06716), targeting sell-side liquidity near prior lows (~1.06700).",
    "Step 5: Confirmed trade success as price respected the inverted FVG zone, retraced to the 0.5 level, and continued downward to hit the sell-side liquidity target."
  ],
  "outcome": "Trade executed successfully: short entry at consequent encroachment (~1.0875), stop above 1.06716, target at ~1.06700; price reached target, achieving ~1R+ profit.",
  "lessons": "Inverted fair value gaps act as strong reaction zones; the 50% consequent encroachment provides a tighter, higher-probability entry than the full gap boundary. Always require a liquidity sweep and close beyond the FVG to confirm inversion.",
